    <p>
        
            
                 
            
        
        June 28, 2009<br><br>On our spiritual journey, it can become evident that we need God's help&mdash;we need God's grace to get us through. Without it, we get hopelessly stuck in this world without a way out.<br><br>So we must pray for and accept that grace. However, there are a few basic different types of grace: sanctifying grace and actual grace. Knowing the difference can help us even more to know what is happening supernaturally in our relationship with God, and motivate us to pursue spiritual growth with even more vigor.<br><br>The information in this article comes from a Catholic article that I found.<br><br><a href="http://www.catholic.com/library/Grace_What_It_Is.asp" target="_blank">Grace: What It Is and What It Does</a><br><br><h3>Sanctifying Grace</h3><br><br>Sanctifying grace is grace that remains within the soul. It is that which gives the soul a supernatural nature, that is capable of going to heaven after death, or at least purgatory. It is grace that binds us to God in a relationship with Him. It is sanctifying grace that  makes us holy before God.<br><br>How do we lose sanctifying grace? By sinning mortally. Any mortal sin completely cuts off our relationship with God, removing all sanctifying grace, defiling the soul.<br><br>However, even venial sin can weaken our supply of sanctifying grace if practiced regularly. This is why all sin is to be avoided.<br><br>If the soul does not have sanctifying grace at death, then it goes to hell, according to Catholic doctrine. Thus the name of "mortal sin"&mdash;sin that leads to death.<br><br><h3>Actual Grace</h3><br><br>Actual grace comes from outside of the soul. Of course it still comes from God, but it is when He pushes us to perform something that will restore or strengthen our sanctifying grace, and our relationship with Him. So to Catholics, actual grace might be when you feel a nudge to pray, to read the Bible, attend Mass, or go to confession.<br><br><h3>Grace for Non-Catholics</h3><br><br>Every step in our lives leads us either to or away from God, no matter what your beliefs are. If you pray, you have taken yet another step toward Him, strengthening your relationship with God that much more. If you do something immoral, then you have weakened that relationship.<br><div style="width:300px;margin:12px 12px 12px 0;clear:both;float:left"><script type="text/javascript"><!--
google_ad_client = "pub-7242869414180671";
/* C2 300x250 */
google_ad_slot = "1297666708";
google_ad_width = 300;
google_ad_height = 250;
//-->
</script>
<script type="text/javascript"
src="http://pagead2.googlesyndication.com/pagead/show_ads.js">
</script></div> <br><br>To me, sanctifying grace is God's grace that purifies us and helps us to become holier in our spiritual journey. If we are completely without it, then it is so much harder to do what we need to do to grow closer to God. We might be overtaken by the temptations of the world and fall off the spiritual path entirely. If we have God's grace, and accept it, then we are more receptive to spiritual practices and worship that will help us to grow even closer and take another step in our spiritual growth.<br><br>Actual grace is those little nudges that we have. If you haven't prayed for a while, or any other spiritual practice that you might to, you might start to feel guilty about that, or just have an urge that you really should begin to soon. Once you have started, that builds up sanctifying grace, making your soul even holier, and it is actual grace that pushes you to keep doing that spiritual practice every day.<br><br>It is the nature of the darkness in the world, sin if you want to call it that, that makes us want to backslide and just miss a day. And as everyone well knows, if you just miss one day, you may as well given up. One day turns into two, and two days turn into three, and pretty soon you have completely stopped.<br><br>So it takes a cooperation between us and God to take on those practices that will help us in our spiritual growth the most. If we accept it, it can still be challenging, but it is much easier than if we reject that grace. Then we are hopelessly stuck in the cycle without god's help and the help of the Holy Spirit.
   </p>
    

