        July 7, 2009<br><br>Yes it is informative and a thought provoking teaching, especially concerning grace. I hadn't thought about sanctification doctrines in a long time, since it is rarely a subject of sermons. The Pentecostal Holiness preachers speak a lot about it, as a separate work of the Holy Spirit, as something a person will know has happened because they are lifted above ongoing temptation to sin. <br><br>There is also a debate among Protestants about whether a person can lose what they have been given and scriptures can be used by either side in defense of their position. I think the author was only presenting the one position on it even though many protestants believe a person can neglect or trample upon their gifts from God or turn back once they have come to know God. <br><br>I know the Catholic church does a great service to it's members in the study and interpretation of biblical concepts and I have read on other Catholic forums how some Catholics are critical of protestants for their varying denominations. I myself believe that everything is as it should be, that every person's walk with God is personal to them, and that everyone is called to perform a unique function within the body of Christ. As long as a person knows in their own spirit that they are doing their best to follow the Holy Spirit then each one must go where they feel led. I respect that some people feel led to serve Christ in the Catholic church, even though I personally don't feel drawn there.</span>
