        July 6, 2009<br><br>That is a very interesting article that does make some good points. I would only caution that, as far as Protestant beliefs and teachings are concerned, to be able to point out errors in the beliefs of another group from the outside, one must first have a full and clear understanding of all the beliefs of the other group. As a non-Catholic, most of what the author said protestants believe, I found as foreign as Catholics must find it when someone says they worship Mary.     <br><br>In other words, the best person to explain Catholic beliefs is a Catholic and the best person to explain a certain protestant doctrine would be a member of that denomination. The author of this article attempts several times to paint all non-Catholic Christians with a broad brush of one common doctrine concerning topics such as salvation, sanctification, justification and sin. There are many protestant denominations and while those beliefs mentioned in the article may be held by some, there are many that hold beliefs very similar to those of the author. <br><br>It seems useless in a way to point out doctrinal differences because teachings and doctrines themselves do not have any power to save, sanctify or justify. The Holy Spirit does these works in the lives of people who submit to God through Christ. I think most doctrines arise from our attempts to explain or describe what the Holy Spirit did after the fact. For those experiencing a work of the Spirit, no doctrines are needed.</span>
